{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 PURGATORIO CANTO 33}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 1-3.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The last canto of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio }{\plain \fs24 \f1 begins, like those of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , with poetry \softline
(see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXIV.1 and }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXIII.1-39).  In all three cases, the poem cited is in another voice \softline
than Dante's.  In the first two cases this voice is Latin, first that of Venantius Fortunatus (his \softline
hymn of the cross), now that of David (his hymn for the desolation of Jerusalem, Psalm 78 [79], \softline
which begins, 'O God, the heathen have come into your inheritance').  Thus do the seven virtues \softline
respond to the present culminating moment in the history of the Church Militant.  As Benvenuto \softline
explains (comm. to these verses), just as the various gentile nations had invaded and oppressed \softline
the Holy Land because of the sins of the Jews, so now has God again allowed foreigners, in this \softline
case the French, to take possession of holy Church because of the sins of the latter-day 'Romans.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab How much of the Psalm is sung is not discernible, but probably more than the first few \softline
words, since we are told that the weeping ladies sing alternating verses.  Singleton (comm. to \softline
verse 1) suggests that the first eight verses would have been appropriate.  Bosco/Reggio (comm. \softline
to verse 1) point out that, beginning with its ninth verse, the Psalm is more optimistic, asking for \softline
God's help and hoping for His intervention.  For a similar question regarding the singing of a \softline
Psalm, see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XXX.82-84.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 4-6.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Beatrice's first response to the singing of the Psalm is to join in its sense of \softline
desolation.  Her sadness is such that even Mary's grief at the foot of the cross for her dead son \softline
was only slightly more profound.  Mary grieves for the death of Jesus, Beatrice for the desolation \softline
of his mystical body, the Church.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 7-12.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The words that Beatrice sings reflect closely Jesus's words to his disciples (John \softline
16:16), '}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 A little while and you shall not see me; and again a little while and you shall see me,}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
because I go to the Father.'  Since the disciples are puzzled by these words, Jesus explains them: \softline
Now they may weep, but their sorrow will be turned to joy (John 16:20).  The disciples are finally \softline
won over, finally believe that Jesus comes from God (John 16:30).  Jesus ends his remarks by \softline
promising them peace after their tribulation and concludes, 'I have overcome the world' (John \softline
16:33).  Thus do these twelve opening verses of the last canto of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  move from a tragic \softline
sense of loss to a celebratory and comic vision of the eventual triumph of Christ and his Church.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Beatrice's words also have a particular and local meaning for Dante, who wept at her \softline
death and thought he had lost her forever; she has come back into his life.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 13-15.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This tercet reminds the reader exactly who is present in this scene (see the note to \softline
}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purg}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . XXXII.88), Beatrice, her handmaids (the seven virtues), Dante, Matelda, and Statius.  Not \softline
only is the Church Triumphant no longer in sight, the Church Militant has been dragged off to \softline
France.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The way in which Statius is referred to ('the sage who had remained') reminds the reader, \softline
yet again, of the absence of Virgil, denied this moment.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 16-18.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Those that allegorize the nine steps taken by Beatrice argue that they represent the \softline
years between the accession of Pope Clement V in 1305, who agreed to King Philip's desire to \softline
move the papacy to France (which he did in 1309), and the deaths of Clement and Philip in 1314, \softline
thus possibly allowing the tenth step to point to the advent of the new leader in 1315.  About such 
things there can be little or no certainty, but the hypothesis is attractive.  Nonetheless, one should \softline
probably be aware that, except for a rather contorted effort by Francesco da Buti (comm. to vv. \softline
16-30), none of the early commentators, generally so fond of allegorizing, offers anything more \softline
than a literal reading of the detail.  The allegorical reading of the ten steps as ten years is a \softline
nineteenth- and twentieth-century discovery, e.g., as it is found in Carroll (comm. to vv. 16-45).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 23.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This is the first time Beatrice addresses Dante as 'brother.'  (She will do so on only \softline
three later occasions: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . IV.100; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VII.58; }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Par}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VII.130).  For the importance and \softline
distribution of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 frate}{\plain \fs24 \f1  in the three }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 cantiche}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , see the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  IV.127.  One \softline
senses, again, that her desire to rebuke Dante is (temporarily) suspended.  But see vv. 85-90.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Beatrice for the first time, and in keeping with the spirit of her citation of John 16:16 in \softline
vv. 10-12, turns her attention to the future, and to Dante's future, now that the world's and his \softline
own sinful past have been dealt with.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 25-28.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Benvenuto (comm. to vv. 25-30) compares Dante to a student in the presence of \softline
his teacher, and indeed this is the opening moment in what might be called Dante's education in \softline
theology, which will last for another thirty cantos.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 31-33.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   Before she presents her prophecy, Beatrice charges Dante with the responsibility \softline
for reporting it precisely, not in the mode of a man who is talking in his sleep.  Almost all the \softline
commentators take the passage literally and as applying in some general way.  But Beatrice's \softline
words are very hard on poor Dante, since she makes it clear that, at least in her (infallible) \softline
opinion, his actual words, uttered at some previous time, have indeed been correctly characterized \softline
in this way.  But when?  Perhaps the later passage in this canto (vv. 85-90) that is devoted to his \softline
previous intellectual meanderings may shed some light on exactly what she means.  For now the \softline
subject is left unexplored.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The importance of the rebuke, which passes mainly unobserved in the commentaries, is \softline
underlined by its difference from a similar rebuke.  Mattalia (comm. to verse 33) is alone in \softline
thinking of that one (if he draws no conclusion from his notice of it): }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Purgatorio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XV.120-123, \softline
when Virgil believes that Dante, beholding an ecstatic vision, is merely drunk or asleep.  Now \softline
Beatrice reverses the situation: when Dante has considered himself 'awake' and eloquent, he has \softline
been, in fact, 'talking in his sleep.'\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 34-36.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The language, referring to the destruction of the Church as detailed in the \softline
preceding canto, is distinctly reflective of the Apocalypse (Apoc. 17:8, 'The beast that you saw \softline
was, and is not').  For clear discussions of the terms 'apocalypticism' and 'millenarianism' and the \softline
differences between them, see Richard Emmerson ("The Secret," }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 American Historical Review}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
104 [1999]), pp. 1610-13.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab The word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 suppe}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (here translated 'hindrance' only to make sense in its context) has been \softline
variously understood.  Many of the early commentators believed it referred to the cakes left on \softline
the tomb of a murderer's victim in a Greek custom reborn in Florence; if the murderer came to the \softline
tomb and ate of these cakes for nine consecutive days, he would then be safe from the offended \softline
family's vengeance (and for that reason the families of the slain person would keep watch over the \softline
tomb).  See Portirelli (comm. to these verses) for a restatement of this interpretation, which is at \softline
least as old as the commentary of Jacopo della Lana.  Others think the reference is to the bread 
soaked in wine on which an oath is sworn between vassal and lord; still others of the offal which \softline
the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 veltro}{\plain \fs24 \f1  will despise (see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inf}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.103), and which is related to the 'sop' to Cerberus of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Aeneid}{\plain \fs24 \f1  \softline
VI.420.  None of these 'sops', however, would seem to offer a cause for fear, and are thus difficult \softline
to rationalize in this context.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 37-42.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The opening verses of Beatrice's extended prophecy seem clearly to indicate that \softline
the one who will come is related to the eagle of empire, i.e., that beneficent Roman empire that \softline
had begun so well under Augustus and then had become corrupt.  It seems difficult to believe that \softline
this, as some maintain, is not an imperial prophecy.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 43-45.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   This enigmatic passage has drawn an extraordinary amount of contradictory \softline
opinion.  For a review of the entire question, see Pietro Mazzamuto, "Cinquecento diece e \softline
cinque" (ED.1970.2), pp. 10b-14b.  It is also helpful to consult Charles Davis's similar review of \softline
the first and similar prophecy in the poem, the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 veltro}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (hound) of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.101 ("veltro" \softline
[ED.1976.5], pp. 908a-912b). Most now argue, whether or not they believe that the number, if \softline
expressed by the Roman numerals DXV, is an anagram of }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 DUX}{\plain \fs24 \f1  (or 'leader' [the Roman 'V' and 'U' \softline
being equivalent letters]), that the context of the passage makes it apparent that Beatrice is here \softline
indicating the advent of a temporal leader, one who will deal with the excesses of the King of \softline
France and the delinquent Church.  Further, if the canto is taken as having been written before his \softline
death in August of 1313, many believe that the prophecy points to Henry VII.  Some also believe \softline
that if the first reference is to a political leader, it also points beyond him to the second coming of \softline
Christ, the final emperor.  See Hollander (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Allegory in Dante's "Commedia"}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Princeton: Princeton \softline
University Press, 1969]), pp. 184-90, and the note to }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Inferno}{\plain \fs24 \f1  I.100-105.  A standard and useful \softline
treatment of the problem remains that of Moore (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Studies in Dante}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , Third Series: }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Miscellaneous \softline
Essays}{\plain \fs24 \f1  [Oxford: Clarendon, 1968 (1903)]), pp. 253-83.\par
