}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 46-51.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The general sense of this passage is clear: future events will make plain the terms \softline
of the cloudy prophecy, which is compared to those made by Themis (Ovid, }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Metam}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . I.375-394) \softline
and by the Sphinx.  Both of these monstrous females later appear in the same passage in Ovid \softline
(}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Metam}{\plain \fs24 \f1 . VII.759-765), where their hatred of humans is, as here, described in terms of the loss of \softline
human and animal life in the countryside.  The key lines in the modern text of Ovid run as follows: \softline
'Carmina La{\f3 \'56}ades non intellecta priorum / solverat ingeniis...' (The son of Laius [Oedipus] solved \softline
the riddles which had baffled the intellects of all before him).  We are close to being absolutely \softline
sure, however, that the text as Dante knew it substituted 'Na{\f3 \'56}ades' for 'La{\f3 \'56}ades' and showed a \softline
plural form of the verb (}{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 solverant}{\plain \fs24 \f1 ).  And so Dante believed that it was the Naiads, water nymphs, \softline
who had solved the riddle of the Sphinx.  This was the cruel monster who cast herself down from \softline
her rock, whence she had been killing clueless Thebans, once Oedipus realized that the variously \softline
footed creature in her riddle was man (the story that we know from Sophocles' }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Oedipus}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , \softline
unknown, like nearly all of Greek letters, to Dante).\par
}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab Dante does not 'nod' often, but this is one of the most egregious errors in the }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Comedy}{\plain \fs24 \f1 , \softline
even if it has some reasonable excuse behind it.  In fact, all of the early commentators accept \softline
